    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-30T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-30T12:00:00-05:00" n="529"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d529">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 103.94/495</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-30T17:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 30, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.06 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2338. For <persName corresp="#p_BBM1">Baruch</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_SLL1">Summers</persName>:</p>
                <p>Returned to London from Paris on account of important meeting of Transport
                    Council today and Financial Council tomorrow, see <pb facs="0701" n="609"
                        xml:id="pg_609"/> our 2279 for <persName>Heidrich</persName> from
                        <persName>Patterson</persName>.<note n="1" xml:id="d529fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> I want to personally urge you to have all our programmes
                    frankly submitted to programme committees. We do not commit ourselves to abide
                    by any recommendations that programme committees may make, but any refusal to
                    submit our data on the ground that it may interfere with our supplies will be
                    taken advantage of and it is wholly unwarranted. We should deal frankly and
                    honestly with all of these programmes and have nothing to lose thereby but
                    everything to gain. Under these conditions, I want your personal interest in
                    insisting that data be furnished to the programme committees.</p>
                <p>See our 2274 for <persName>Scott</persName> from
                        <persName>Patterson</persName>.<note n="1" xml:id="d529fn3">Not
                        printed.</note> British Government at the solicitation of <persName>Andrew
                        Weir</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d529fn2">British Surveyor-General of Supply.</note> will
                    probably insist on 10 per cent compensation for handling Australian wool
                    situation. This is simply compensation to trade interests and [should] not be
                    permitted by us. I shall formally decline to accept this and urge if British
                    Government insist upon it that representation be made by our State Department to
                    British Foreign Office in regard to establishing this precedent [which] may
                    result in similar action on our part in regard to our fundamental commodities.
                    This is an absolute violation of the policy we have been pursuing of giving the
                    Allies the benefit of our prices. If we were to propose a similar charge against
                    wheat and cotton furnished the Allies, you can appreciate what it would mean.
                    …</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
